to have a cousin personally drive your donkey there in a 1950s-era Buick loaded with bricks on the back. What an interesting burden to be transported piece by piece on the face of what may be Sergio Leone’s film arena 60 years later. The cement layering of the building, the hand-wheel mounted milk churns all seem like modern gear here. Time passes and yet stops. Old habits die hard.

When Wadjda is told that she can’t participate in the school-wide talent show

because girls don’t participate in school-wide talent exhibits, she quickly calls upon the force of law with her quick bullshit-detection, glove-slapping.
